iOn April 8, 2014, the renowned open-source SSL support software		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOpenSSL exposed the "Heartbleed" vulnerability. Against this		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ivulnerability, nearly all current IDS systems and firewalls are		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idefenseless.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSSL, fully known as Secure Socket Layer, is a widely used encryption		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprotocol on the internet that prevents data from being eavesdropped		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iduring transmission between users and servers. OpenSSL is an		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iopen-source SSL support software. By invoking it, any software can		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ieasily implement SSL encrypted connections without needing to research		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSSL from scratch. The HTTPS protocol utilizes SSL to protect user		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idata, and major websites redirect users to HTTPS pages during login to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isafeguard user information.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, the "Heartbleed" vulnerability exposed in OpenSSL has caused		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imassive repercussions for all such software. What does this		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ivulnerability lead to? Random memory reads, 64KB at a time.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i64KB per read—and this attack can be repeated continuously without		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idetection by firewalls. Thus, hackers can repeatedly traverse the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ientire server's memory to extract critical data such as user		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipasswords, cookies, and website source code. Using this information,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihackers can steal accounts and leverage the source code to launch		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifurther attacks on servers.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe vulnerability affects OpenSSL versions 1.01 to 1.01f. The latest		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iversion 1.01g has patched this vulnerability, and OpenSSL versions		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprior to 1.01 are unaffected.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThis vulnerability impacts:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- (Almost) all SSL-enabled web servers on Linux, BSD, Mac, and similar		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iplatforms, including Apache, Nginx, Lighttpd, Tengine (essentially		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iNginx), etc. Affected websites include critical platforms like Alipay,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iTaobao, and Tencent.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- All open-source web servers with SSL enabled running on Windows		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iplatforms, such as Apache and Nginx.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- (Almost) all SSL-based email services (POP3, IMAP, SMTP), including		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iGmail, QQ Mail, etc.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- All OpenVPN services and other SSL-based VPN services.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
